(appendix
  :book \"book-of-music\"
  :number 1
  :title \"Bach and the Goldberg Variations\"
  :short-title \"bach-goldberg\"
  :estimated-words 1900
  :composer-verified \"Johann Sebastian Bach, born 21 (or 31 — Old Style/New Style) March 1685, Eisenach; died 28 July 1750, Leipzig.\"
  :piece-verified \"Aria mit verschiedenen Veränderungen, BWV 988, published 1741 in Nuremberg by Balthasar Schmid. Second part of the Clavier-Übung (Keyboard Practice) series.\"
  :philosopher-weave (jung peirce aristotle wittgenstein-late)

  :prose
\"Johann Sebastian Bach published a piece for two-manual harpsichord in Nuremberg in 1741, in the last decade of his life. He called it *Aria mit verschiedenen Veränderungen* — Aria with Diverse Variations. The title page said nothing about who commissioned it or why. Sixty-one years later, a Bach biographer named Johann Nikolaus Forkel told a story: the piece had been written for a Count Kaiserling, the Russian ambassador to the Saxon court in Dresden, who suffered from insomnia. The Count kept a fourteen-year-old harpsichordist named Johann Gottlieb Goldberg on staff to play for him during sleepless nights, and he asked Bach to write something 'soft and lively' that Goldberg could play. Bach wrote the variations. The Count paid Bach with a golden goblet full of gold coins. From then on, the piece was called the Goldberg Variations.

Modern scholars are skeptical of Forkel's story. Goldberg was fourteen in 1741, which is very young to play the piece — it is among the most demanding works in the harpsichord repertoire. The dedication is not printed on the score, which would be strange if the piece were commissioned. Kaiserling did have a court musician named Goldberg, but the specifics are otherwise undocumented. What is undoubted is the piece itself — thirty variations on an aria, framed by the aria appearing at the start and again at the end. That structure is the piece's true title, and it is one of the most extraordinary structures in music.

# The Aria

The Aria is a slow, ornamented sarabande in G major, thirty-two bars long. It has a memorable descending bass line — the *bass ostinato* — that all thirty variations are built on. The melody in the right hand of the Aria is decorated with grace notes and mordents; it is beautiful but almost incidental. The real material of the piece is not the melody. It is the bass line. Bach discovered — or knew, at fifty-six — that if he could hold the bass line steady across thirty variations, he could put anything in the upper voices and the piece would cohere.

# The Structure of the Thirty

Bach arranged the thirty variations in a plan. Every third variation (Variations 3, 6, 9, 12, 15, 18, 21, 24, 27) is a **canon**, and the canonic interval increases by one step each time. Variation 3 is a canon at the unison — the second voice enters singing the same notes as the first. Variation 6 is a canon at the second — the second voice enters one step up. Variation 9 is at the third; Variation 12 at the fourth; and so on up to Variation 27, a canon at the ninth. This is a systematic project: Bach walks up the intervals of a scale, showing what a canon sounds like at each step.

Between the canons, the other variations alternate between virtuosic display pieces (fast, hand-crossing, sparkling) and reflective, slow, deeply expressive pieces. The pattern is not exactly regular, but the alternation gives the piece its rhythm across the hour.

The last variation, Variation 30, is not a canon. It is a *Quodlibet* — a variation that layers two popular folk melodies over Bach's bass line. The two tunes, which Bach's family would have known and sung together, are 'Ich bin so lang nicht bei dir g'west' (I have been so long away from you) and 'Kraut und Rüben haben mich vertrieben' (Cabbage and turnips have driven me away). The joke is domestic — a family in-joke about mother's cooking and returning home. And the mastery is that Bach fits both tunes over his own bass line at the same time, without breaking the harmonic pattern the piece has held for the previous twenty-nine variations. It is a piece of counterpoint sitting inside a piece of counterpoint.

Then the Aria returns. Same notes as the opening. Not decorated further; not transformed; not varied. Just the Aria, played again as it was played at the beginning.

# What the return means

This is the moment I want to spend the appendix on. Thirty variations. An hour of virtuosic keyboard playing, of intellectual rigor in the canons, of expressive depth in the slow variations, of humor in the Quodlibet. Then the Aria comes back. Unchanged.

What is it supposed to mean?

Different pianists and scholars have offered different readings. Some say the return is about the Aria being unchanged by the journey — the theme has been shown from every possible angle, and it is still itself. Some say the return is about the *listener* being changed by the journey — we hear the same notes differently at the end because we have spent an hour with them. Some say it is about circle and return: a rondo-like structure blown up to enormous scale, where the refrain is the Aria and the episodes are the variations.

I lean toward the second reading, and I want to say why. When we hear the Aria at the start of the piece, we hear a slow, pretty tune with an odd descending bass line. It is charming; we don't know what to do with it. Over the next hour, Bach teaches us what to do with it. He shows us that the bass line contains a canon at every interval; he shows us that a virtuoso can dance over it; he shows us that a folk-song joke can sit on top of it. By the time the Aria returns, we have been given thirty ways of hearing the bass line. When the Aria is played again, we cannot hear it the same way. We hear the bass line as capable of everything we have just heard. The Aria has become an entirely different object without a single note being changed.

This is what I think Bach meant by ending the piece the way he did. It is a lesson in the fact that hearing is not a passive act — that the same notes can mean very different things depending on what you have heard *around* them. He is teaching the ear.

# What we can do in Scheme

We cannot recreate the Goldberg Variations in a small program. But we can build a small demonstration of the principle: state a bass line, then play different things over it, and hear how the different things all get organized by the same bass.

```scheme
;; A short bass line — the ground the variations sit on.
(define bass '(G3 F#3 E3 D3 C3 B2 A2 D3))   ; 8 notes, in G major, ends on the dominant

(define (play-bass)
  (with-dynamics 'mp
    (for-each (lambda (n) (note-play n 'half)) bass)))

;; Variation A — quarter-note melody on top of the bass
(define var-a
  '((G4 quarter) (A4 quarter) (B4 quarter) (D5 quarter)
    (C5 quarter) (B4 quarter) (A4 quarter) (G4 quarter)
    (G4 quarter) (A4 quarter) (G4 quarter) (F#4 quarter)
    (E4 quarter) (F#4 quarter) (G4 quarter) (A4 quarter)))

;; Variation B — eighth-note runs on top of the same bass
(define var-b
  '((G4 eighth) (A4 eighth) (B4 eighth) (C5 eighth)
    (D5 eighth) (C5 eighth) (B4 eighth) (A4 eighth)
    ; ... continues over the same 8 bass notes
    ))

;; Play both together
(define (play-var melody)
  (parallel
    (play-bass)
    (with-dynamics 'mf
      (for-each (lambda (nd) (note-play (car nd) (cadr nd))) melody))))

(play-var var-a)
(play-var var-b)
```

Both variations sit on the same bass line. The melodies are completely different. The listener hears them as related pieces because the bass line is the same. Bach did this thirty times in one work.

# Why this appendix belongs in the book

We've been building a vocabulary — form, harmony, rubato, physical pitch. The Goldberg Variations show that all of these tools can be used in service of one project: the exhaustive exploration of a single musical object. Bach spends an hour on one bass line. Every technique the harpsichord had was brought to bear on this bass line: virtuosic display, contrapuntal canon, homely folk song, meditation. The piece is a demonstration of what serious attention to a small object can produce.

For anyone learning music, or learning to program, or learning any craft where you turn material over and look at it from many sides, the Goldberg Variations is a model of what deep attention looks like. Bach did not add material to make the piece more interesting; he added *ways of hearing the same material*. That is a discipline, and it is one of the highest forms of art we know.

# Recommended listening

Glenn Gould made two famous recordings of the Goldberg Variations, in 1955 and 1981 — both for Columbia (Sony). The 1955 recording is fast, brilliant, and made him famous at twenty-two. The 1981 recording, made shortly before his death at fifty, is slower, more reflective, and treats the Aria's return as a genuine moment of contemplation rather than as a repetition. Both are in most libraries. Listen to both, in order, and notice how the same score can be a young person's piece and an older person's piece.

Wanda Landowska, the great harpsichordist, recorded the piece in 1933 and 1945 on a harpsichord she designed — a large modern instrument, not a period one. These recordings are important historical documents and remain moving despite the different tonal aesthetic.

Any number of modern harpsichordists — Trevor Pinnock, Kenneth Gilbert, Andreas Staier — have recorded the piece on period instruments. These sound different from the piano recordings: quicker to decay, brighter in the upper register, and closer to what Bach's ear would have heard in 1741.

# Sources cited

Johann Nikolaus Forkel, *Über Johann Sebastian Bachs Leben, Kunst und Kunstwerke* (Leipzig, 1802). The Kaiserling-Goldberg story is in Chapter IX.

Christoph Wolff, *Johann Sebastian Bach: The Learned Musician* (Norton, 2000). The standard modern Bach biography, which treats the Forkel story with appropriate skepticism.

Peter Williams, *Bach: The Goldberg Variations* (Cambridge University Press, 2001). A short scholarly guide.

BWV 988 score in facsimile and modern editions is in the public domain and available on IMSLP.

Gould discography from Sony Music Archives; Landowska from RCA Victor and EMI archives; Pinnock from Deutsche Grammophon; Gilbert from Harmonia Mundi; Staier from Harmonia Mundi.\"

  :notes
\"The Kaiserling-Goldberg story is presented honestly — as Forkel's account, not as certain fact. Modern scholarship (Wolff, Williams) treats it skeptically, which we reflect. The canon-at-interval structure is verifiable in the score. The Quodlibet folk-song identifications are standard scholarship (attested in Bach family history — Forkel discusses them, Wolff confirms). All recordings cited are documented in the labels' catalogs.\"

  :philosopher-weave-details
\"Jung: circumambulation — walking around the same object, seeing it from every angle.
Peirce: the bass line as index (physical trace of the harmonic ground) present under every variation.
Aristotle: the aria-variation-aria structure as a whole action with distinct parts.
Wittgenstein-late: the piece as a shared form of life for keyboardists — a work that changes how you hear all other keyboard music once you have inhabited it.\"

  :tie-forward
\"Appendix 2 will look at Debussy — the composer who broke open the harmonic language Bach and Rachmaninoff worked within.\")
")
